Indonesia confirms H5N1 death in mother of 2 earlier victims
------------------------------------------------------------
Indonesia's Ministry of Health has confirmed H5N1 avian flu in the
death of a 29-year-old mother of 2 children who also died of the
disease, according to a report today [14 Nov 2011] from Bird Flu
Information Corner [see [1] above], an Internet message board operated
by Kobe University in Japan and Airlangga University in Indonesia. The
report said the patient, from the resort island of Bali, felt weak,
was coughing, and had breathing difficulty on 15 Oct 2011 when she was
hospitalized. However, she escaped just before she was to be
transferred to a referral hospital and was found in a place of
alternative healing the next day. Her condition deteriorated, and she
died at home on 17 Oct 2011. Her 5-year-old daughter and 10-year-old
son died 9 Oct 2011 and 10 Oct 2011, respectively, of H5N1 avian flu.
Many poultry deaths had been recently reported in the family's flocks
and those of their neighbors. If the woman's death is confirmed by the
World Health Organization (WHO), it would bring Indonesia's official
H5N1 case count to 181, including 150 deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is confirmed now that the death of the mother of the 2 children
resident in Bangli regency, Bali Province, who both died as a result
of avian influenza A/(H5N1) virus infection, was also a consequence of
avian influenza virus infection. While it is likely that the 3 members
of the same family were independently infected from the same source
(diseased poultry), it may be that they shared genetic susceptibility
to infection by the avian virus. No other person in the same village
was reported to have been affected. The situation deserves further
investigation.

According to the most recent WHO statement (see ProMED-mail Avian
influenza, human (64): Indonesia (BA) WHO 20111027.3198) the 2
deceased children were the 180th and 181st cases of avian influenza
A/(H5N1) virus infection in Indonesia. Consequently their recently
deceased mother would be the 182nd case. Hopefully the discrepancy in
numbering will be resolved when the next WHO update is available.

The location of Bangli regency can be found via the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
http://healthmap.org/r/1nkj. - Mod.CP]
